  "prompt": "How long does it take for teeth to relapse (move) after a broken retainer?",
  "response": "The time it takes for teeth to relapse or move after the breakage of a retainer can vary significantly from person to person. Generally, some shifting can begin to occur within a few days to a couple of weeks after losing or breaking a retainer, especially if the retainer was a fixed type. \n\nFactors influencing relapse include:\n\n1. **Duration of Retainer Use**: How long you wore the retainer after orthodontic treatment can affect stability. Longer use typically leads to better retention of tooth position.\n   \n2. **Individual Biology**: Some individuals have teeth that are more prone to movement due to factors like bone density and periodontal health.\n   \n3. **Type of Orthodontic Treatment**: The initial alignment and the way teeth were moved can influence how likely they are to shift after retainers are removed.\n   \n4. **Age**: Younger patients may experience more rapid shifting compared to adults.\n\nTo minimize the risk of shifting, it\u2019s essential to contact your orthodontist as soon as you notice a broken retainer to discuss your options and potentially get a replacement. In the meantime, if possible, wearing the retainer or a temporary solution could help maintain the positioning of your teeth.",
